low to make a proper living, and it became clear to the world that a fairer

00:07:52.110 --> 00:07:57.390
system, similar to the one proposed by Max Havelaar coffee was needed.

00:07:58.543 --> 00:08:05.163
So in the years after this, in the early 1990s various groups came together,

00:08:05.319 --> 00:08:11.199
uniting around the mission to make trade fairer for farmers across the world.

00:08:12.429 --> 00:08:18.549
To try to ensure that they were paid a fair price for the goods that they were

00:08:18.549 --> 00:08:25.189
producing and to ensure that the profits from the work that they were doing were

00:08:25.209 --> 00:08:31.929
going to them, to the farmers, and not to the middleman or large trading companies

00:08:31.929 --> 00:08:36.759
that bought the products from the farmers and then sold them in the developed world.

00:08:38.408 --> 00:08:41.361
We aren't going to go into huge detail in this

00:08:41.361 --> 00:08:47.061
episode about how Fairtrade is structured, but it is now a collection

00:08:47.061 --> 00:08:52.251
of different organisations that span large parts of the world.

00:08:53.357 --> 00:08:59.493
And since the Fairtrade foundation was established in 1992, it

00:08:59.493 --> 00:09:06.538
has grown to over 1.7 million farmers in 75 countries producing

00:09:06.598 --> 00:09:13.738
30,000 different products, all united around a common mission, a common goal.

00:09:14.926 --> 00:09:19.268
And the mission of Fairtrade is pretty simple.

00:09:20.356 --> 00:09:24.716
In Fairtrade's own words, Fairtrade is about better

00:09:24.716 --> 00:09:30.146
prices, decent working conditions, local sustainability

00:09:30.746 --> 00:09:36.176
and fair terms of trade for farmers and workers in the developing world.

00:09:37.505 --> 00:09:44.915
How Fairtrade tries to achieve its mission is also pretty simple, on one level.

00:09:46.125 --> 00:09:51.793
It is all structured around the economist's favourite incentive: price.

00:09:53.164 --> 00:09:56.339
Firstly, there is a minimum price that a

00:09:56.339 --> 00:10:01.769
Fairtrade farmer gets, for the products that he or she sells.

00:10:02.969 --> 00:10:08.579
This means that, even in times when the price of something might go very low,

00:10:09.269 --> 00:10:14.699
that farmer still receives the minimum price for the goods that they sell.

00:10:16.156 --> 00:10:19.808
This means that they can invest for the long-term and they

00:10:19.808 --> 00:10:26.138
don't have to constantly worry about fluctuations in the global price for their products,

00:10:26.648 --> 00:10:32.513
which as we have already mentioned, does happen a lot, there are a lot of fluctuations.

00:10:33.582 --> 00:10:37.004
Secondly, there is something called a Fairtrade

00:10:37.144 --> 00:10:42.034
premium that is paid to the cooperative that the farmer belongs to,

00:10:43.014 --> 00:10:45.864
so premium means an extra price, a higher price.

00:10:46.662 --> 00:10:51.312
The members of the cooperative can choose how this money

00:10:51.312 --> 00:10:57.822
