00:15:06.454 --> 00:15:11.524
So people are prepared to pay a lot more for Fairtrade than they

00:15:11.524 --> 00:15:17.944
actually do, meaning that the Fairtrade farmer is on one level missing

00:15:17.944 --> 00:15:22.504
out on a large amount of money that consumers are prepared to pay.

00:15:24.455 --> 00:15:31.115
As a result of these kinds of criticisms, people and companies have started looking

00:15:31.115 --> 00:15:39.695
out for alternatives, other ways of achieving the mission of Fairtrade, but with different methods.

00:15:40.806 --> 00:15:46.426
From a trade point of view, the main alternative is direct trade.

00:15:47.706 --> 00:15:55.881
This just means that companies buy directly from the farmer or cooperative, and they aren't

00:15:55.881 --> 00:16:03.051
governed by Fairtrade standards that may not be applicable to that farmer or that product.

00:16:04.281 --> 00:16:09.951
The idea behind this is that they can form a long-term relationship, work

00:16:09.951 --> 00:16:16.341
on more equal terms, and it gets rid of some of the bureaucracy, costs

00:16:16.371 --> 00:16:21.665
and inefficiencies and overheads that come with Fairtrade.

00:16:22.890 --> 00:16:28.850
Another interesting development is that retailers and companies that sell things

00:16:28.850 --> 00:16:34.894
like coffee, tea, and chocolate have started their own versions of Fairtrade.

00:16:36.304 --> 00:16:39.964
Sainsbury's, which is one of the biggest supermarket

00:16:39.964 --> 00:16:46.444
chains in the UK, has its own label now called 'Fairly Traded'.

00:16:47.792 --> 00:16:51.122
McDonald's has its own programme for its coffee.

00:16:51.602 --> 00:16:57.152
Nestle has its own version and Starbucks has its own one and they're all different.

00:16:58.201 --> 00:17:02.851
They are all supposedly doing this because they have decided

00:17:02.851 --> 00:17:07.265
that Fairtrade, the organisation, isn't the most effective

00:17:07.265 --> 00:17:13.865
way of them reaching their sustainability goals and that they can have more

00:17:13.865 --> 00:17:19.655
of an impact by bringing this activity in-house, by doing it themselves.

00:17:21.695 --> 00:17:27.419
Of course, people are quite sceptical about this because if there isn't

00:17:27.479 --> 00:17:34.572
any kind of external organisation that provides oversight, that reviews

00:17:34.572 --> 00:17:42.282
the terms of the trade between the company and the farmer, then we risk returning to a

00:17:42.282 --> 00:17:48.822
situation where the trade between the farmer and the buyer really isn't so fair anymore.

00:17:50.892 --> 00:17:58.362
The other risk here is that consumers, so people like me and you, we've got so used to

00:17:58.632 --> 00:18:05.982
different terms being thrown around: Fairtrade, organic, biological, fairly treated, ethically

00:18:05.982 --> 00:18:12.162
sourced, carbon neutral, and so on that we have become numb to what they really mean.

00:18:14.032 --> 00:18:20.607
You might just see a label or logo on a chocolate bar or banana or packet

00:18:20.607 --> 00:18:25.647
of coffee and think, well, that's probably a good thing, and put it in

00:18:25.647 --> 00:18:30.807
your shopping basket without really knowing anything about what it means.

00:18:32.530 --> 00:18:39.090
And at least with Fairtrade, it is a global body, a global organisation with

00:18:39.250 --> 00:18:45.930
recognised standards, and you know that it is deeply aligned with the farmer's interests.

00:18:47.009 --> 00:18:53.571
As we know from scandals like the Volkswagen one, when a company is in

00:18:53.571 --> 00:19:00.231
charge of monitoring its own standards, the incentives aren't aligned, and this means

00:19:00.321 --> 00:19:06.531
the company often doesn't do a very good job, to put it politely, of assessing itself.

00:19:08.661 --> 00:19:13.221
So Fairtrade is coming under quite a bit of pressure from

00:19:13.221 --> 00:19:18.171
various different market forces and its future is slightly uncertain.

00:19:19.451 --> 00:19:21.821
It needs the buyers, it needs the companies

00:19:21.821 --> 00:19:25.841
to buy from its cooperatives, otherwise there is no Fairtrade.

00:19:27.036 --> 00:19:30.966
And of course it needs the farmers, but it also needs the

00:19:30.966 --> 00:19:36.246
consumers to still opt for and demand Fairtrade products.

00:19:37.206 --> 00:19:41.226
And if it can't do this, it risks becoming irrelevant.

00:19:43.426 --> 00:19:47.656
Luckily it doesn't seem like that will happen in the very near future,

00:19:48.046 --> 00:19:54.226
but it is certainly a risk for Fairtrade, for the collectives it works with, and for

00:19:54.226 --> 00:19:59.766
the farmers who have been getting a fair deal through being part of the programme.

00:20:01.153 --> 00:20:06.020
Whatever happens to Fairtrade in the future, what is undeniable

00:20:06.350 --> 00:20:11.330
is that it has been an important force in educating consumers

00:20:11.600 --> 00:20:16.160
